<BaseLayout title={pageTitle}>
  <h1>Echoes on the Water, V in the Sky</h1>
  <p>
    Geese are remarkable birds known for their distinctive V-formation during
    migration. As waterfowl, they are perfectly at home both in the sky and on
    the water. Their loud, honking calls are a familiar sound in many parts of
    the world, echoing across lakes and fields. These birds belong to the
    Anatidae family, which also includes swans and ducks. They possess strong
    wings and webbed feet, making them powerful swimmers and flyers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The social structure of geese is surprisingly complex and loyal. They are
    known for forming strong family bonds and often mate for life. A male goose,
    or gander, is fiercely protective of his partner and their young, called
    goslings. This protective nature can sometimes be perceived as aggression
    towards intruders. The flock works together, communicating constantly to
    ensure safety and coordinate movement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Geese have a long and shared history with humans. Domesticated for
    centuries, they provide meat, eggs, and soft down feathers for pillows and
    blankets. In urban parks, they can be a common sight, sometimes becoming a
    nuisance with their droppings and territorial behavior. Despite their
    occasional feistiness, their determined spirit and strong family ties earn
    them a measure of respect.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
